```java
public class Department {
    String dept;
    List<Employee> employees;
    double minSal;
    double maxSal;

    public void addEmployee(Employee emp){
        if (employees.isEmpty()) {
            minSal = emp.getSalary();
        }
        if (minSal > emp.getSalary()) {
            minSal = emp.getSalary();
        }
        if (maxSal < emp.getSalary()) {
            maxSal = emp.getSalary();
        }
    }
}
```

In this code, `minSal` is initialized to the salary of the first employee in the department. Then, for each subsequent employee, it checks if their salary is less than the current minimum salary. If it is, it updates `minSal`. The maximum salary is updated in the same way.

Please note that you need to handle the case where the department is empty before trying to find the minimum salary.

Also, you should consider adding a check to ensure that the salary is not negative or zero, as these are not valid salaries.

This approach will work for any number of employees in the department.

